<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 23 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Radio Netherlands Wereld Omroep, 22 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://www.rnw.nl/hotspots/html/dut030422.html>

Fear of fowl pest mutation
--------------------------
With 2 cases of fowl pest [highly pathogenic avian influenza - HPAI] now
reported across the Dutch border, the authorities in Belgium are taking no
chances. After imposing a transport ban in the affected areas, they have
stepped up an emergency vaccination campaign to protect people from the
virus that causes fowl pest in chickens. All non-professional
chicken-rearers and others coming into contact with the animals are now
advised to get an anti-flu injection or to take antiviral medicines.
The move comes after a Dutch veterinarian died of pneumonia last Thursday
after catching avian flu while working at an infected poultry farm. The 57
year old vet had not been vaccinated or taken antiviral drugs. His death
has fueled fears that the virus has mutated to a human strain in much the
same way as an animal disease is believed to be the origin of severe acute
respiratory syndrome (SARS). [Though there has been speculation, so far
there are no scientifically-based data indicating SARS' origin in animals.
- Mod.AS]
Experts, however, are playing down the chances that fowl pest could cause a
full-blown epidemic in humans. A World Health Organization spokesman said
on Saturday that the disease did not appear to spread easily from human to
human.
Dutch virologist Ab Osterhaus commented on national television that
mutation of the virus was theoretically possible but practically
improbable. He explained that this would require the exchange of DNA in a
human simultaneously infected with avian influenza and a similar human
variety. With the flu season over, the chances of that happening were
remote, he said.
In another interview this morning, Dr Osterhaus described the special
emergency measures taken by Belgium as "overkill". "The preventive
treatment of those few additional people doesn't make much sense," he
remarked. In his view, the approach adopted by the Dutch government should
be adequate, if followed meticulously. This means that all those involved
in the fight against fowl pest are obliged to take special precautions,
including vaccination and the use of antiviral drugs.
******
