Date: Wed, 23 pr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ministry of Agriculture, Nature management and Fisheries (LNV)
press release, 22 Apr 2003 [translated from Dutch by Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.minlnv.nl/infomart/dossiers/vogelpest/>

Independent inquiry into the death of a veterinarian
----------------------------------------------------
State secretary Ross (VWS) and minister Veerman (LNV) have decided to carry
out an independent inquiry into the circumstances of the death of the 57
year old veterinarian in Den Bosch from serious pneumonia. Since
fowl-plague [highly pathogenic avian influenza - HPAI] virus was detected
in the veterinarian's lungs, and while no other explanation for the
progression of his disease has been found, there is a strong indication
that his death is the outcome of infection with the HPAI virus.
******
[3]
Date: Wed, 23 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ministry of Agriculture, Nature management and Fisheries (LNV)
press release, 20 Apr 2003 [translated from Dutch by Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.minvws.nl/zoeken.html?folder=548&envelope=1317§ion=21>

Questions about the antiviral medication oseltamivir (Tamiflu)
--------------------------------------------------------------
1. What is oseltamivir (Tamiflu)?
Tamiflu is an antiviral medication [neuraminidase inhibitor. - Mod.SH]
active against influenza viruses.
2. How does it work?
It prevents the early multiplication of viruses in the body, so that cells
already infected do not reinfect other cells.
3. Why should oseltamivir be used?
Oseltamivir is used to prevent the infection of humans with the fowl-plague
virus during the fight against the epidemic. This way, the people exposed
to the virus through their activities in the infected holdings are
protected. Such people include assessors, veterinarians engaged in sample
collection and culling activities, or tenants, residents, and laborers on
the infected or suspected farms. In some cases the drug may be used to
treat people who are already infected with the virus.
4. Why should a flu jab [vaccination] be given in addition to oseltamivir?
The flu jab is the best way to prevent infection with the currently
circulating human influenza virus. This is crucial to prevent the fowl-pest
virus and the common [human] virus from co-infecting the same person,
enabling the creation of a new virus.
5. How long can oseltamivir be taken?
No data are available regarding the effects of extended use. Data from
prevention studies, however, showed no indications limiting its use for 6
weeks. Under [medical] supervision, the medication can be taken for longer
periods.
6. Does oseltamivir influence the ability to drive or use machinery?
As far as is known, oseltamivir does not affect driving fitness or the
ability to operate machinery.
7. Are alternative drugs to oseltamivir available?
No, at present no other neuraminidase inhibitors are available. [Zanamivir
is another neuraminidase inhibitor, introduced before oseltamivir, whose
efficacy appears to be similar. - Mod.SH]
8. Can oseltamivir be used during pregnancy?
No sufficient data on the use of oseltamivir in pregnant women are
available. Consequently, its use during pregnancy may be considered only
for cases in which the potential benefit for the mother outweighs the
potential risk to the fetus.
9. Can oseltamivir be used during breast feeding?
Here also, oseltamivir can be used only when the potential benefit for the
mother justifies the potential risk to the baby.
