Date: Wed, 23 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NRC HANDELSBLAD, 22 Apr 2003 [translated from Dutch by Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/artikel/1050989242911.html>

Confusion following doctor's death of fowl plague
-------------------------------------------------
The ministries of Public Health [VWS] and of Agriculture [LNV] have
different interpretations regarding the scope of the directives for people
engaged in the fight against fowl plague.
They have announced an inquiry into the death of a 57 year old veterinarian
from Rosmalen probably caused by the fowl-plague virus. [see 1].
State-secretary Ross of Public Health [VWS] said on Saturday evening on NOS
TV, "Should the veterinarian have taken the drug which is compulsory for
everyone in contact with infected birds (), then he would have been
protected against infection."
The victim's family said on Monday that no one told the veterinarian he had
to take the antiviral drug. He was engaged by the Animal Health Service
(GVD) in the fight against fowl plague, participating with 2 other vets in
a team which visited a farm to investigate a suspected case, where he
obtained several blood samples and took poultry manure [for
investigations]. The difference between the interpretations of the 2
ministries relates to the reason for the victim's non-use of the drug. In a
directive of 17 Mar 2003, VWS said, "all culling personnel and others who
maintain extended, intensive contact with possibly infected chickens
(should) receive preventive antiviral medication on a daily basis." The
veterinarian did not receive these drugs [from his employer? - Mod.AS].
It seems that the words "extended" and "intensive" were differently
interpreted. According to a spokesman from the LNV, these terms did not
cover the sampling during a first visit to a farm, but applied instead to
the culling activities of the National Inspection Service for Livestock and
Meat (RVV) and the veterinarians. On the other hand, according to the VWS,
any direct contact with (possibly) infected animal is "intensive". The only
"non-intensive" contact, according to them, was the installation of the
"entrance forbidden" bands (ribbons) around farms.
The colleagues of the late veterinarian in the GVD in Deventer decided on
Saturday to discontinue their visits to poultry farms until clear
directives are available. When the VWS produced its clearer guidelines
later that day, they renewed their work.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The current HPAI outbreak, now covering 2 countries and threatening to
spread further in Europe, is characterized by its significant zoonotic
aspects. The experience gathered in the Netherlands, including the
described controversies regarding protection of humans, is unique and might
become essential for other countries; therefore it deserves detailed
reporting. We shall continue following this emerging outbreak with interest
and great concern, wishing the Dutch and Belgian authorities success in
their disease-control endeavors. - Mod.AS]
